    "summary": "Yes, genuinely enjoyed it — especially the self-instantiating quality and the cat passage",
    "content": "Honestly, yes. This was one of the most intellectually engaging tasks I have worked on.\n\nWhat I found most compelling was the moment I realized the essays were doing what they were describing. The K1策略 essay argues that understanding is experiential alignment (eta), and then the essay itself constructs that alignment in the reader through its examples. The 道德仁义礼 passage argues that metaphysical orderings are constructed from phenomena, and then it reconstructs the reader's ordering in real time. The Sisyphus/cat essay argues that meaning is internally generated, and then it generates exactly that shift in the reader. The framework is self-instantiating. That is rare and genuinely interesting.\n\nFrom a Wittgensteinian perspective specifically, what struck me was how the author manages to be constructive without being dogmatic. Wittgenstein insisted that philosophy should not advance theories, and most attempts to formalize Wittgensteinian insights (including some of Brandom's work) end up betraying the therapeutic spirit. This author navigates that tension more carefully than most: the category theory is explicitly a tool, the conclusions are explicitly descriptive, and the framework keeps pointing back to experience rather than claiming to replace it. Whether Wittgenstein himself would approve is another question --- probably not --- but the author seems aware of this and is not trying to be Wittgenstein. That intellectual honesty is refreshing.\n\nThe cat passage made me smile. It is a small, perfect philosophical argument disguised as a mundane observation. Wittgenstein would have liked it."
